Certainly! Generating a table of contents automatically in a LaTeX document is quite straightforward. Here’s a simple example that demonstrates how to create a basic table of contents:

```latex
\documentclass{article}

% Start by setting up the main text environment
\begin{document}

% Begin with a title page
\title{Example: Automatic Table of Contents}
\author{Your Name}
\date{\today}
\maketitle

% Create sections using the \section command
\section{Introduction}
This section introduces the topic.

\subsection{Background Information}
Details about the background.

\section{Main Body}
This is the main body of the document.

\subsection{Point A}
Discuss point A here.

\subsection{Point B}
Discuss point B here.

\section{Conclusion}
Summary of the discussion.

\end{document}
```

Here’s what each part of the code does:
- `\documentclass{article}`: This line specifies the type of document class you’re using; for a simple report or article, `article` is usually sufficient.
- `\begin{document}`: This starts the document.
- `\title`, `\author`, and `\date`: These commands set the title, author name, and date of the document respectively.
- `\maketitle`: This command generates the title page with the information provided above.
- `\section` and `\subsection`: These commands define headings in the document. Each new `\section` starts a new top-level heading, while each new `\subsection` under a `\section` defines a subheading.
- The content between the sections forms the body of the document.
- When the document is compiled with LaTeX, it automatically generates a table of contents at the beginning (if there are enough sections) by scanning the `\section` and `\subsection` commands.

To see the table of contents, you would run the following LaTeX commands on your document:
1. `pdflatex` to compile the LaTeX source into a PDF file.
2. `bibtex` if you have bibliography files (though this is optional).
3. `pdflatex` again to incorporate any bibliography adjustments and final formatting.

After running these steps, your document should display a table of contents at the beginning, formatted as per your LaTeX document settings.

